# Corrected Response

The common cold is usually caused by viruses, so antibiotics are not effective against it. Most people recover within 7 to 10 days with rest, adequate fluids, and symptom relief such as over-the-counter medications when appropriate.

Antibiotics should only be used when prescribed for bacterial infections. Taking antibiotics unnecessarily can contribute to antibiotic resistance and may cause side effects such as allergic reactions or digestive problems.

If symptoms become severe, last longer than expected, or you develop signs of a bacterial infection—such as persistent high fever, difficulty breathing, or severe facial pain—you should seek medical evaluation.

